            <section>
              <title>The week of interest rates</title>
              <chapter>                                                         <!--[0-N]-->
              <paragraph>This week Central Banks from 15 countries or jurisdictions are scheduled to decide on monetary policy. Rates typically reflect the health of individual economies, as in a perfect scenario, Central Banks tend to rise rates when the economy is growing and therefore instigate inflation. Rate cuts on the other hand, are a way to stimulate a struggling economy.</paragraph>                                          <!--[0-N]-->
              <paragraph>The Bank of Japan said on Tuesday it would maintain its massive asset buying program at existing levels but offered a bleaker view of the economy, suggesting it may roll out more stimulus as it struggles to reach an elusive inflation target.</paragraph>                                                                   <!--[0-N]-->
              <paragraph>The SNB is using negative interest rates, coupled with an unspecified amount of foreign currency purchases, to weaken the Swiss franc and protect exports to the euro zone, Switzerland’s biggest trading partner.</paragraph>                                          <!--[0-N]-->
            </chapter>
